{"decision":"not_done","recommend_promotion":false,"confidence":0.74,"summary":"The implementation covers the main token list/detail/revoke flow and the required deterministic commands reportedly pass, but I found substantive gaps against the spec/exit criteria. Token detail reconstructs claims with the current/default issuer instead of the issuer used when the token was issued, because issuer is not persisted on OAuthIssuedToken. That can make the claims UI inaccurate for tokens issued from request-origin/base-URL contexts. Also, the @token-revocation coverage proves active and revoked filtering, but does not prove expired-token filtering despite that being an explicit exit criterion.","satisfied_exit_criteria":["Token UI lists issued token metadata and shows detail without returning or redisplaying raw access token values.","Revocation persists revokedAt and existing bearer validation rejects revoked tokens with 401 for subsequent runtime calls.","The required commands in the provided deterministic check summary passed: npm run test:unit, npm run test:e2e -- --grep @token-revocation, and npm run verify.","The task maps to docs/product-specs/oauth-consent-and-token-runtime.md and stays scoped to issued token operations."],"missing_requirements":["Persist and expose enough token metadata for claim detail to show accurate reconstructed claims, especially iss matching the token as issued.","Add deterministic coverage that expired issued tokens are distinguished by the token list/filter path, ideally in the @token-revocation E2E or focused unit coverage tied to this task."],"human_review_triggers":["Required checks do not fully prove the claimed active/expired/revoked filter behavior.","Implementation claim detail can contradict the product/spec intent to expose useful stored token claims for debugging."]}
